00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:21.873
Well, there was one
show in particular

00:05:21.873 --> 00:05:24.350
that I wish I could have seen.

00:05:24.350 --> 00:05:26.530
It was at a place
called Examination Hall,

00:05:26.530 --> 00:05:28.840
which is Trinity College
in Dublin, Ireland,

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:33.310
specifically on
October 21, 1977.

00:05:33.310 --> 00:05:35.380
And Trinity Hall-- excuse me.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:37.300
Examination Hall
at Trinity College

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:39.940
isn't necessarily--
it's not the Forum.

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:40.990
It's not Monterey Jazz.

00:05:40.990 --> 00:05:42.610
It's not Oakland Colosseum.

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:45.042
It's actually a room
where students take tests.

00:05:45.042 --> 00:05:47.500
And it was the room of a very,
very, very important concert

00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:50.000
that actually effected my
life and affected the lives

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.424
of many people that I know.

00:05:52.424 --> 00:05:54.590
And when you think about a
room like this it's like,

00:05:54.590 --> 00:05:58.870
got large cathedral halls, it's
very narrow, it's very boring.

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:02.440
But inside this room
on October 21 in 1977

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:06.444
about 1,200 Dublin
teenagers came in from--

00:06:06.444 --> 00:06:07.110
Dublin, Ireland.

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:09.520
I'm sorry if I didn't tell
you it was Dublin, Ireland--

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:11.620
but Dublin teenagers
came in to see

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:14.500
what was to become the
very first punk rock

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:16.540
show in Ireland.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:18.649
Now, these kids have given
way-- like every kid,

00:06:18.649 --> 00:06:20.440
they're looking for
context in their lives.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.939
They're looking for a way to
express themselves against what

00:06:22.939 --> 00:06:24.280
was going on around them.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:27.070
And frankly, they
were tired of, like,

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:30.950
handlebar mustaches and
disco polyester pants,

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:32.300
so they did something new.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:34.120
And they decided
to tear those pants

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:37.510
and do, like,
Cleopatra-inspired mascara,

00:06:37.510 --> 00:06:41.410
and do Anglo-European Mohawks
to be able to go to this show.

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:43.210
It was a big, big, big event.

00:06:43.210 --> 00:06:45.580
And more importantly, what
was important to understand

00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:48.500
at the time in Dublin, Ireland--
what was happening in Ireland?

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.570
It was a place that was trying
to find its national identity,

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:53.800
really, once again.

00:06:53.800 --> 00:06:57.430
You know, just about 88 miles
north of the venue in Belfast

00:06:57.430 --> 00:06:59.620
was a place of, as
many of you know,

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:02.860
fantastic sectarian violence.

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:07.360
There was terrorist attacks,
like, Molotov cocktails,

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:09.910
gunshots.

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:12.520
That was an average Tuesday
for people in the north.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:14.710
So really Ireland,
at this point,

00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:17.080
was a place of trying to
find itself through violence,

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:18.580
through nationalism.

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:21.680
I don't know of any that
sounds familiar to you at all.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:23.780
But inside this
room these students

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:25.580
were trying to figure
out who they were.

00:07:25.580 --> 00:07:30.320
And the band that was
coming on stage in 1977

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:33.380
was a new punk band
called The Clash.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:34.880
Now, if you're under
40 you probably

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:36.980
don't know who
they are, but this

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:38.750
was a band that had
only been around

00:07:38.750 --> 00:07:41.150
at this point for
just, like, one year.

00:07:41.150 --> 00:07:42.706
And the lead singer--

00:07:42.706 --> 00:07:43.580
I'm not sure if-- oh.

00:07:43.580 --> 00:07:44.705
He's the guy in the middle.

00:07:44.705 --> 00:07:46.040
His name is Joe Strummer--

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:48.620
had actually been born
a child of privilege.

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.350
You know, Joe Strummer was a
diplomat's son whose parents

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:53.420
dropped him off at a--

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:56.345
basically to be raised
by another school.

00:07:56.345 --> 00:07:58.220
And he realized that
privilege wasn't the way

00:07:58.220 --> 00:07:59.540
that he wanted to live.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:01.270
So when he got
out of high school

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:03.260
he started living in the
south side of London.

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:05.360
He lived with the
disenfranchised

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:07.790
and the minorities, and
actually became an advocate

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:08.540
in his own way.

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:11.630
And his advocacy was to
find a way to play music.

00:08:11.630 --> 00:08:14.840
And that's how The
Clash got started.

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:18.140
And so when Joe got
started, really it

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:20.822
was a way of being able to
express what was inside of him

00:08:20.822 --> 00:08:21.780
and bring it to others.

00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:24.730
And punk rock really became
the recipe and The Clash

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:26.340
were just the chefs.

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:28.400
Now, it's important
to note that what

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:31.490
was happening behind the band.

00:08:31.490 --> 00:08:35.230
And this is obviously
Belfast in 1977.

00:08:35.230 --> 00:08:37.690
But this is a
picture of the tour

00:08:37.690 --> 00:08:42.760
in which they were playing at
this time on October 21, 1977.

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:45.220
And what was behind
the band is a backdrop

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:48.570
of a picture of a
race riot in London.

00:08:48.570 --> 00:08:50.200
And this is where
black communities

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:53.470
were coming together to be able
to stand up for their rights.

00:08:53.470 --> 00:08:55.450
And these disenfranchised
minorities

00:08:55.450 --> 00:08:58.540
were really a big part of
who Joe was standing up for

00:08:58.540 --> 00:09:00.100
and The Clash were
standing up for.

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:02.440
In fact, really what's
interesting about the clash

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:05.740
is that they were a white band
playing to white audiences

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:07.450
about black music.

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.690
And when Joe stepped up to
the mic for the first time,

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:15.684
the crowd went wild because
he yelled out "white riot."

00:09:15.684 --> 00:09:17.225
I'm going to-- I'm
not going to sing.

00:09:17.225 --> 00:09:17.750
Don't worry.

00:09:17.750 --> 00:09:19.970
Because you don't want that.

00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:21.710
But I'm going to
read them to you.

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:22.430
"White riot.

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:23.600
I want a riot.

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:26.000
White riot, a riot of my own.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.190
Black people got
a lot of problems,

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:30.200
but they don't mind
throwing a brick.

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:33.392
White people go to school,
where they teach you

00:09:33.392 --> 00:09:34.100
how to be thick."

00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:41.210
You see, what Joe is saying
to this mainly white audience

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:44.090
was that black
people have to riot.

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:47.790
They have to riot to survive,
but white people don't.

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:51.290
And as a person who has grown--
he had grown up with privilege.

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:55.040
His message was, if you can't
find your own riot, if you

00:09:55.040 --> 00:09:56.990
can't stand up for
something, you're

00:09:56.990 --> 00:09:58.580
going to live a half life.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:01.100
You're just going to be
another, in his words,

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:03.980
another "thick" bloke.

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:06.650
His message to everyone,
and our message today,

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:08.930
is to find your riot.

00:10:08.930 --> 00:10:10.820
Find something to stand up for.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:14.330
Find something
bigger than yourself.

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:16.640
Now, back in the back
of Examination Hall

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:19.220
were four teenagers
who were taking this

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:21.820
all in as if it
was, like, you know,

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:27.177
a messianic prophetic preacher
at a tent evangelist show.

00:10:27.177 --> 00:10:28.760
They were just looking
at this as just

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:30.970
being blown away at everything
that they were seeing.

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:33.376
And they realized inside
of them that this--

00:10:33.376 --> 00:10:34.640
this was it.

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:36.510
This was their message.

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:38.060
They were going to
find their riot.

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:40.325
And again, you know,
anyone under 40 years old

00:10:40.325 --> 00:10:41.700
probably won't
know who they are,

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:43.850
but they were just
here a few months ago.

00:10:43.850 --> 00:10:46.730
They went on to become U2.

00:10:46.730 --> 00:10:48.230
This band found
their riot, and they

00:10:48.230 --> 00:10:51.110
realized that it wasn't
just about what you do

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:54.010
and how you live
and what you get,

00:10:54.010 --> 00:10:58.240
but it's about how you leverage
who you are and what you are

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:03.050
and what you're good at for
the problems of other people

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:04.700
who can never repay you.

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:09.740
Purpose isn't
happiness, and we're

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:13.150
going to talk a little bit
further about that today.

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:14.992
But these lads were
able to find it,

00:11:14.992 --> 00:11:16.200
were able to find their riot.

00:11:18.980 --> 00:11:21.440
"Purpose" is a big
word, and it's one

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.290
that I think we don't
pay enough attention to.

00:11:24.290 --> 00:11:27.590
I actually believe that we're
living in a global purpose

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:28.700
crisis.

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:31.610
Only today we have infinite
suitors coming at us

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:34.050
at all times of the
day promising purpose,

00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:38.120
but in reality we're just
being offered amusement.

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:41.210
You see, many of us have
reached the very top

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:44.780
of Maslow's hierarchy of needs
and we're no longer foraging

00:11:44.780 --> 00:11:47.490
for food and for shelter.

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:51.800
We're forging for something
that matters in our lives.

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:54.760
I think this guy said it best.

00:11:54.760 --> 00:11:58.302
"He who has a why
can endure any how."

00:11:58.302 --> 00:12:01.074
And I actually believe that
standing up for something

00:12:01.074 --> 00:12:02.490
that you want
changed in the world

00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:06.150
is actually not noble
or selfless or otherly

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:09.010
or something to be respected.

00:12:09.010 --> 00:12:12.640
It's actually selfish, and
it's actually survival.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:15.640
Because the only way that
you're going to be able to find

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:20.770
true purpose is to take
on the problems of others.

00:12:20.770 --> 00:12:25.270
You see, in this equation
purpose is our why to live,

00:12:25.270 --> 00:12:27.390
not just our how.

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:29.250
We're handling
everythings every day.

00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:31.095
The promise is how to be helpy--

00:12:31.095 --> 00:12:33.450
the promises how to be happy--

00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:36.870
and helpy-- and these are
our how, but they're not--

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:38.330
they're not our why.

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:40.990
And the pursuit of happiness
is pretty straightforward.

00:12:40.990 --> 00:12:44.760
It's found through
acquiring and achieving.

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:46.725
But how do we find our why?

00:12:46.725 --> 00:12:47.850
How do we find our purpose?

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:52.950
I've had a book out
for a few months

00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:55.804
and, you know, you don't
really pay attention

00:12:55.804 --> 00:12:57.720
to the people who you
don't know that read it.

00:12:57.720 --> 00:13:01.200
You pay attention to the people
who you do know who read it.

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:02.987
And specifically you
really pay attention

00:13:02.987 --> 00:13:05.070
to the people who you do
know who haven't read it,

00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:06.653
because that's where
it gets personal.

00:13:06.653 --> 00:13:08.540
[CHUCKLES]

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:11.287
And one person in particular--
and I actually have to say,

00:13:11.287 --> 00:13:12.620
this friend of mine is someone--

00:13:12.620 --> 00:13:13.520
I won't say who he is--

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:15.645
he's actually someone I
kind of wrote the book for.

00:13:15.645 --> 00:13:19.040
Like, the archetype,
the type of person.

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:21.650
And he told me-- he's like, you
know, this is great and all,

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:23.464
but I've got,
like, bills to pay,

00:13:23.464 --> 00:13:25.130
and I've got kids to
get through school,

00:13:25.130 --> 00:13:26.510
and I've got all the rest of it.

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:28.760
And purpose and
meaning, frankly--

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:29.650
they sound otherly.

00:13:29.650 --> 00:13:30.824
They sound meta.

00:13:30.824 --> 00:13:32.490
I hear people tell
me this all the time.

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:34.100
It's like, yeah, I'll--

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:37.680
eventually I'll buy a Tesla,
but it's not for right now.

00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:38.900
That's what purpose is.

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:40.790
It's a Tesla in
most people's lives.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:42.890
[CHUCKLES]

00:13:42.890 --> 00:13:45.310
This is because we think
of an understanding

00:13:45.310 --> 00:13:47.620
that the why of our life,
the pursuit of meaning,

00:13:47.620 --> 00:13:50.920
is somehow extra, something
that we can figure out

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:53.440
once we have our how,
once we have everything

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.170
that we feel like we need.

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:58.670
There's lots of
definitions for purpose,

00:13:58.670 --> 00:14:02.310
but this is the one that
I find the most helpful.

00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:06.350
Purpose isn't how much you can
give or what you can donate

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:08.880
or what cause you're
associated with.

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:09.860
Listen to this.

00:14:09.860 --> 00:14:15.730
It's finding what the world
needs from you, finding out

00:14:15.730 --> 00:14:18.040
what the world needs from you.

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:19.650
Here's the thing.

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:21.870
Charity is going to tell you--

00:14:21.870 --> 00:14:23.850
and I've run one for 10 years--

00:14:23.850 --> 00:14:25.480
will tell you that
the world needs

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:27.610
you to give to support that.

00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:28.860
I actually don't believe that.

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:31.080
They need you to give, and
it is extremely important

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:32.820
that we all support charities.

00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:35.660
But that's not purpose.

00:14:35.660 --> 00:14:38.930
You were designed to fix
problems in the world.

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:44.120
If you aren't fixing your own
needs of just having to put

00:14:44.120 --> 00:14:46.490
a roof over your head
and food on the plate,

00:14:46.490 --> 00:14:48.620
you're actually designed--
and your purpose--

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:51.830
is to fix the needs and
fix the problems of others.

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:52.910
It's not ancillary.

00:14:52.910 --> 00:14:56.770
It's actually a big,
big part of your why.

00:14:56.770 --> 00:14:59.840
So the point of my book
and the point of my talk

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:03.890
is to try to solve a
lot of problems at once.

00:15:03.890 --> 00:15:08.840
What if we could change the
world and improve our lives?

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:11.480
You see, my friend who
doesn't have time for this,

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:14.840
he just needs to make them--
he's got problems in his life.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:15.900
Those are more important.

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:19.270
And frankly, I don't
argue with him.

00:15:19.270 --> 00:15:22.360
But he's missing out,
because he doesn't know

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:24.710
what the world needs from him.

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:28.070
What if we could solve
our "how to live" problems

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:31.640
while also solving our
"why am I here" problems,

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:34.520
while also solving
the problems of others

00:15:34.520 --> 00:15:36.700
who can never pay us back?

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:39.130
In my book I propose
a model to be

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:40.840
able to help us understand this.

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:44.610
And I've actually
arranged all of humanity

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:48.990
into two different groups, two
different types of poverties.

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:52.030
The first poverty is
a poverty of means.

00:15:52.030 --> 00:15:54.900
This is the poverty that
most of us are familiar with.

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:57.300
This is the poverty
that we see on our feeds

00:15:57.300 --> 00:15:58.710
and we see in the news.

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:01.240
We know what this
poverty looks like.

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:04.907
But I've put a word next to it
that I think is helpful for us

00:16:04.907 --> 00:16:05.490
to understand.

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:07.470
And Jacquelline was
talking earlier about,

00:16:07.470 --> 00:16:09.720
in some ways, how
I see the world.

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:13.140
The word "means" is very,
very important here.

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:17.670
"Means" actually means
an action or a system

00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:20.550
by which a result
is brought about.

00:16:20.550 --> 00:16:21.050
OK.

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.850
So to bring that down,
a "poverty of means"

00:16:23.850 --> 00:16:27.210
simply means that there's
an action or a system that's

00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:28.790
missing.

00:16:28.790 --> 00:16:31.880
Poverty is no longer
just about a condition.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:33.640
Right?

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:36.170
It's that something's missing.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:40.400
So when we say that there's
844 million people who

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:43.640
don't have access to clean
water, what we're saying

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:47.990
is there's a poverty of means
to wells to offer clean water.

00:16:47.990 --> 00:16:52.499
When we say there's 400 million
people that are suffering just

00:16:52.499 --> 00:16:54.290
for basic health, we're
saying that there's

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:58.610
a poverty of means to medicine
and care to that health.

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:02.330
When we say that there's 40
million people plus living

00:17:02.330 --> 00:17:07.081
in slavery today, it's a
poverty of means of justice.

00:17:07.081 --> 00:17:08.680
Now, this is the
poverty of means

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:13.480
that I wrestle with every
day, the poverty of justice.

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:15.970
We're missing an
action or a system

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:17.740
where there should be one.

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:20.800
My day job is to build a
means and to fix a system that

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:23.380
allows children to be
exploited every day in order

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:24.800
to support our lifestyles.

00:17:27.510 --> 00:17:29.310
Slavery is reprehensible.

00:17:29.310 --> 00:17:33.030
And it actually needs
more than our attention

00:17:33.030 --> 00:17:36.770
and our care and our reposts.

00:17:36.770 --> 00:17:39.080
It's a thriving business
and it's a moral outrage,

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:43.670
because it's a
system that works.

00:17:43.670 --> 00:17:48.160
So it needs an action or a
system to make it stop working.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:51.880
This is extremely evident
when I visit places

00:17:51.880 --> 00:17:55.400
like Ghana out on Lake
Volta and I meet little boys

00:17:55.400 --> 00:17:59.390
like this, Ebenezer, who
works on a boat every day

00:17:59.390 --> 00:18:02.536
for 17 hours a
day to catch fish.

00:18:02.536 --> 00:18:03.410
He's controlled by a.

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:08.420
Master Ebenezer is suffering
a poverty of means.

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:10.400
And so is his little
brother, who's

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:12.780
asleep at the top of the boat.

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:14.580
And when I talked
to his master--

00:18:14.580 --> 00:18:16.230
who is in the red
shirt-- and I ask him

00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:19.680
why is this little
boy working and not

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:23.160
in school, his answer to
me is, if he doesn't work,

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:25.380
I don't eat.

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:28.090
I'm sorry, but that's
also a poverty of means.

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:32.070
So you can get how slavery
is a hot mess on this planet,

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:34.170
and it needs more
than just donations.

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:38.520
It needs a system, and it
needs an action to break it.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:39.990
And it's heartbreaking.

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:42.400
But our breaking
hearts aren't enough.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.530
It actually needs us to step in.

00:18:47.440 --> 00:18:49.390
The other poverty that
I want to talk about

00:18:49.390 --> 00:18:52.480
is also fantastically-insidious.

00:18:52.480 --> 00:18:55.080
It's a poverty of meaning.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:57.690
This is a poverty
that many of us--

00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:00.060
some of us, and certainly
people we know--

00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:02.490
are living beneath
its poverty line.

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.810
It's not one that people
talk about very often,

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:06.544
but it still claims lives.

00:19:06.544 --> 00:19:07.710
I'm going to say that again.

00:19:07.710 --> 00:19:11.670
It claims the lives of
thousands of people every year.

00:19:11.670 --> 00:19:15.410
It causes disease,
uproots communities,

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:20.040
and has even played a role in
creating a few wars or two.

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:22.290
While it doesn't rob us of
food or water or medicine

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:26.220
or justice, it steals something
that's very valuable to us all.

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:27.900
We already saw it.

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:30.150
It steals our why.

00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:33.810
It takes away our why to live.

00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:36.380
And as we learned earlier,
it's difficult to know

00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:40.400
how to live if we don't
have a why, if we don't know

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:43.190
what the world needs from us.

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:46.340
What's scary is that many of us
are scraping by in our lives,

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:50.120
unaware that this poverty
is eating at our heels.

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.160
While it doesn't take
nearly the amount of lives

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:55.970
a year that the poverty of
means takes, it's still lethal.

00:19:55.970 --> 00:19:57.100
And we can see it.

00:19:57.100 --> 00:20:00.220
Maybe not directly, but
indirectly in the data,

00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:05.700
where 50% of people on social
media between 18 and 34

00:20:05.700 --> 00:20:11.300
feel ugly and
worthless and otherly.

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:16.290
And 30% of those people feel
extreme amounts of loneliness.

00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:18.540
In fact, one in five
people in America

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:22.110
feel extremely and
debilitatingly lonely.

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:24.110
And all the data that's
coming out on loneliness

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:27.230
is directing-- is saying
to us, that it's actually

00:20:27.230 --> 00:20:31.850
creating health problems,
heart disease, diabetes.

00:20:31.850 --> 00:20:33.680
These things are connected.

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:38.930
Meaning and health and
wealth and how we live

00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:40.460
are all connected.

00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:42.530
If we don't know
our why and we don't

00:20:42.530 --> 00:20:46.250
know what the world wants from
us, in some ways we perish.

00:20:46.250 --> 00:20:51.080
Not just existentially,
literally perish.

00:20:51.080 --> 00:20:55.130
If anyone understands this
existential and physical

00:20:55.130 --> 00:21:00.410
perishing best it's Dr. Frankl.

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:04.010
Dr. Frankl understood this
need better than anyone,

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:05.780
because he wrote in
his popular book,

00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:07.670
"Man's Search for Meaning."

00:21:07.670 --> 00:21:10.649
If you read it you'll learn
that he was a psychiatrist.

00:21:10.649 --> 00:21:11.690
It's a very popular book.

00:21:11.690 --> 00:21:13.356
You might have already
actually read it.

00:21:13.356 --> 00:21:15.860
He was a psychiatrist around
World War II that ended up

00:21:15.860 --> 00:21:18.270
in a concentration camp.

00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:21.910
And he tasked himself
to save the people who

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:24.590
were killing themselves.

00:21:24.590 --> 00:21:26.960
And he knew he could
tell when someone

00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:29.860
was going to kill themselves
because they started

00:21:29.860 --> 00:21:31.960
smoking their cigarettes.

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:33.790
You see, cigarettes
in concentration camps

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:34.610
were currency.

00:21:34.610 --> 00:21:35.600
You didn't smoke them.

00:21:35.600 --> 00:21:39.720
You traded them for things
you needed like food or a day

00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:41.420
off from work.

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:45.450
But when you started smoking
the only thing of value

00:21:45.450 --> 00:21:48.370
you have in your
life, Dr. Frankl

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:52.290
knew that they were close
to committing suicide.

00:21:52.290 --> 00:21:57.760
And his primary argument
with every one of them

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:00.790
was that the world needed
something for them.

00:22:00.790 --> 00:22:05.260
There was still something that
the world needed from them.

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:09.010
It was his main argument
inside of a concentration camp

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:13.300
to help people understand
not just a poverty of means,

00:22:13.300 --> 00:22:15.450
but their own
poverty of meaning.

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.860
His message, like
Joe's, is the same.

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:22.960
The world wants
something from you.

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:26.070
The world wants your riot.

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:27.830
It wants you to know.

00:22:27.830 --> 00:22:30.890
It wants to know what you
care about, and actually

00:22:30.890 --> 00:22:32.751
wants you to act on it.

00:22:32.751 --> 00:22:35.250
If we don't find our riot, we
suffer and the world around us

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:37.000
misses a chance to improve.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.040
Your riot is the voice
inside of you that says,

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:43.060
I wish something was
different in the world.

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:46.350
Now, I found my
riot later in life.

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:48.660
I came upon the issue
of human trafficking

00:22:48.660 --> 00:22:50.080
and it hijacked my heart.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:53.790
And I had every opportunity to
keep moving with what was then

00:22:53.790 --> 00:22:55.610
a music career.

00:22:55.610 --> 00:22:57.410
But I said, you know, I just--

00:22:57.410 --> 00:22:59.937
I'm going to give this
thing that's inside of me

00:22:59.937 --> 00:23:00.770
a little bit of gas.

00:23:00.770 --> 00:23:01.580
Not a lot.

00:23:01.580 --> 00:23:03.060
I don't want to change my life.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:04.460
I don't to do this
for 10 years--

00:23:04.460 --> 00:23:05.360
even though I have.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:06.429
I don't want to do that.

00:23:06.429 --> 00:23:07.220
I'm just going to--

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:08.960
I'm just going to lob
one over the fence.

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:10.340
I want to try something.

00:23:10.340 --> 00:23:13.370
Because what I saw working
around this issue 10 years ago,

00:23:13.370 --> 00:23:15.794
what I saw people doing,
frankly didn't seem like enough.

00:23:15.794 --> 00:23:17.960
And at the time I was a
part of the music community.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:21.230
I'm like, well, can't have
a movement without music.

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:22.880
Let's get it on.

00:23:22.880 --> 00:23:26.090
And so I pulled a bunch of
musicians together during

00:23:26.090 --> 00:23:29.530
Grammys week in 2007
and I said, let's--

00:23:29.530 --> 00:23:31.520
here was my business plan.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:34.550
Let's make some-- let's
film some performances

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:37.399
and then let's give them away,
and we'll talk about slavery

00:23:37.399 --> 00:23:37.940
on top of it.

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:39.050
That was my business plan.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:41.120
And actually people agreed.

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:44.540
And so people came to a
studio in Santa Monica

00:23:44.540 --> 00:23:46.790
and filmed these beautiful
performances for me

00:23:46.790 --> 00:23:49.410
that I had no idea
what to do with.

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:51.450
And after two days of
filming I'm like, wow,

00:23:51.450 --> 00:23:52.500
that went really good.

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:54.000
Like, people really
love doing this.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:54.830
Guess what?

00:23:54.830 --> 00:23:58.260
People actually love doing what
they're good at to help others.

00:23:58.260 --> 00:24:00.680
I think we're on to something.

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:02.440
And so I decided to do it again.

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:05.420
I did it in New York, and
then in Austin, in London.

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:07.550
And all these musicians
started coming together.

00:24:07.550 --> 00:24:09.470
And then I thought, well, we
should get some smart people

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:10.460
to talk about it.

00:24:10.460 --> 00:24:12.800
So let's call up Nick
Kristof and Dr. Cornel West

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:14.380
and Madeline Albright.

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:17.690
And I quickly learned how,
you know, films like Borat

00:24:17.690 --> 00:24:19.730
