of a berth of the
opportunity to try things,

00:35:59.240 --> 00:36:02.420
I think you can create
some wonderful things here

00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:03.360
with this network.

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:05.840
But again-- and I know it's
weird to say this to Google,

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:07.830
but I really do think
you have to think small.

00:36:07.830 --> 00:36:08.330
You know?

00:36:08.330 --> 00:36:13.190
Like, people come to me all the
time, like, let's do a concert,

00:36:13.190 --> 00:36:15.410
or let's create an
app that ends slavery.

00:36:15.410 --> 00:36:18.230
It's like, you know, let's
just get a few companies

00:36:18.230 --> 00:36:21.040
to look at their supply chain.

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:22.330
Wow, that's boring.

00:36:22.330 --> 00:36:24.719
My goodness is it so impactful.

00:36:24.719 --> 00:36:27.010
We're not, like, playing with
thousands of dollars now.

00:36:27.010 --> 00:36:28.970
We're playing with billions.

00:36:28.970 --> 00:36:29.470
You know?

00:36:29.470 --> 00:36:32.230
But it's not-- it's
not as sexy as, like--

00:36:32.230 --> 00:36:34.330
so I think that we really
do need to scale back

00:36:34.330 --> 00:36:37.199
our ambitions around what
something looks like and put

00:36:37.199 --> 00:36:38.740
more of our ambition
on, like, what's

00:36:38.740 --> 00:36:41.035
something that can
just help out a little?

00:36:41.035 --> 00:36:44.200
You know, helping out a
kid with their homework

00:36:44.200 --> 00:36:46.420
seems like a little,
but it's a lot.

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:47.729
It's fantastic.

00:36:47.729 --> 00:36:49.270
So I think we have
to kind of divorce

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:54.010
ourselves from the idea that
all change is glamorous.

00:36:54.010 --> 00:36:56.280
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:37:00.510
I was just wondering how
you measure your impact?

00:37:00.510 --> 00:37:03.180
Is it, like, in a
financial system

00:37:03.180 --> 00:37:05.810
as we are currently used to?

00:37:05.810 --> 00:37:11.190
You know, like, by quarter by
quarter, this kind of stuff?

00:37:11.190 --> 00:37:13.670
Or do you base as well
with public policies,

00:37:13.670 --> 00:37:14.985
implementations, for example?

00:37:14.985 --> 00:37:17.610
With sustainable development
goals for the UN--

00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:20.790
I used to work for the UN and
then I moved to go Google.

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:22.920
I did some partnerships
back in Brazil

00:37:22.920 --> 00:37:24.090
with indigenous communities.

00:37:24.090 --> 00:37:28.080
But then I see our public
policies going backwards.

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:28.740
You know?

00:37:28.740 --> 00:37:32.340
Like, I see the indigenous
rights in Brazil, for example,

00:37:32.340 --> 00:37:34.470
you know, being disrespected.

00:37:34.470 --> 00:37:37.559
So I'm glad to hear from
you as well about that.

00:37:37.559 --> 00:37:38.392
JUSTIN DILLON: Yeah.

00:37:38.392 --> 00:37:43.740
I think change is juggling
chainsaws and walking.

00:37:43.740 --> 00:37:45.450
That's what it looks like.

00:37:45.450 --> 00:37:47.570
Because one chain
saw is public policy,

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:49.290
one chain saw is
the marketplace,

00:37:49.290 --> 00:37:52.350
one chain saw is the
economy of attention.

00:37:52.350 --> 00:37:55.460
It's very expensive to get into.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:56.990
It isn't just one thing.

00:37:56.990 --> 00:37:59.120
And over the last
10 years we've seen

00:37:59.120 --> 00:38:03.110
enormous growth, an enormous
difference made around slavery.

00:38:03.110 --> 00:38:05.030
But I can't tell you
how many rooms I've

00:38:05.030 --> 00:38:08.360
been in-- important
rooms, like, you know,

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:10.100
rooms you've heard
of where people

00:38:10.100 --> 00:38:12.800
slam their hand on the table and
say, you're not doing enough,

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:15.860
and then they go back to
their pulpit or they go back

00:38:15.860 --> 00:38:19.520
to their desk and go
back on with their job.

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:22.870
Because people expect, when
something's really bad,

00:38:22.870 --> 00:38:27.680
like slavery, that it should
just be fixed very easily.

00:38:27.680 --> 00:38:32.340
It's entrenched in
everything we do.

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:34.350
And so it requires some move--

00:38:34.350 --> 00:38:35.990
a little bit of
movement on policy.

00:38:35.990 --> 00:38:37.760
Some movement in
the marketplace.

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:40.970
Some movement around consumers,
I mean, in the work that we do.

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:43.040
And I would assume it's
the same everywhere else.

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:46.142
For us we had to, like, roll
it all back as a company.

00:38:46.142 --> 00:38:48.350
We had to roll it all back
to, like, what does change

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:49.230
look like for us?

00:38:49.230 --> 00:38:49.730
Oh.

00:38:49.730 --> 00:38:50.510
Guess what?

00:38:50.510 --> 00:38:51.800
It's really boring.

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:53.870
It actually means
how many companies

00:38:53.870 --> 00:38:56.000
are looking at how
many of their suppliers

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:00.500
and measuring where slavery
might be in that supply chain?

00:39:00.500 --> 00:39:02.056
And it turns out
that, as we started

00:39:02.056 --> 00:39:04.430
moving towards that as a
company and trying to figure out

00:39:04.430 --> 00:39:06.638
how to measure that-- because
you can't fix a problem

00:39:06.638 --> 00:39:07.430
you can't measure.

00:39:07.430 --> 00:39:12.110
And to my knowledge there has
been no census on slaves since,

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:15.130
like, maybe 150 years ago.

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:16.849
So how do you
measure a problem--

00:39:16.849 --> 00:39:18.640
how do you fix a problem
you can't measure?

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:19.830
So we're measuring
it for companies

00:39:19.830 --> 00:39:21.960
and actually giving them a way
to be able to step forward.

00:39:21.960 --> 00:39:23.280
[SNAPS] Now the lights went on.

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:24.810
Now we can actually
look at how we

00:39:24.810 --> 00:39:27.180
can fix a problem that's
been with us for a long time

00:39:27.180 --> 00:39:28.960
and probably will continue.

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:30.725
So it does take a
bit of iteration,

00:39:30.725 --> 00:39:32.100
but I think
sometimes people just

00:39:32.100 --> 00:39:34.860
go hard on public policy
being-- oh, if we can just get

00:39:34.860 --> 00:39:36.570
a law passed, that'll be it.

00:39:36.570 --> 00:39:39.270
And it's just-- that's
just one chainsaw.

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:40.160
My opinion.

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:44.100
Did all of those, like,
weird metaphors help at all?

00:39:44.100 --> 00:39:45.060
Because I have a--

00:39:45.060 --> 00:39:47.600
I don't get the sense they did.

00:39:47.600 --> 00:39:49.390
We can sidebar.

00:39:49.390 --> 00:39:51.290
Yeah.

00:39:51.290 --> 00:39:55.130
AUDIENCE: Any other questions?

00:39:55.130 --> 00:39:58.200
AUDIENCE: So you talked about
the supply chain for companies.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:00.510
Where is your company
going and where do you

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:03.540
need the help in
your company itself?

00:40:03.540 --> 00:40:06.090
JUSTIN DILLON: We just
need as many companies

00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:08.335
using our software as possible.

00:40:08.335 --> 00:40:09.710
We're the only
software out there

00:40:09.710 --> 00:40:12.350
that can measure slavery
beyond the first-tier supplier.

00:40:12.350 --> 00:40:14.689
And actually most
people will say, oh,

00:40:14.689 --> 00:40:16.730
we're talking to all of
our first-tier suppliers.

00:40:16.730 --> 00:40:18.470
There's 10,000 or 20,000.

00:40:18.470 --> 00:40:19.320
They're all good.

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:21.200
It's usually not where
the problems are.

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:23.300
We actually need
to be able to use

00:40:23.300 --> 00:40:25.040
optics, the optics
we provide, to be

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:27.860
able to push beyond tier-one
and understand where

00:40:27.860 --> 00:40:30.440
the problems are, and get those
relationships between buyer

00:40:30.440 --> 00:40:33.380
and seller to kind of push
further and change behavior

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:34.400
in the supply chain.

00:40:34.400 --> 00:40:37.010
And we're seeing it happen
at a very large scale.

00:40:37.010 --> 00:40:40.010
But it is going to take the
coalition of the willing,

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:42.710
so to speak, in the marketplace
to all work together.

00:40:42.710 --> 00:40:45.264
And in a competitive marketplace
where one company doesn't

00:40:45.264 --> 00:40:47.930
want to share all their secrets,
this isn't something you want--

00:40:47.930 --> 00:40:50.030
I'd like for people to be
competitive on slavery.

00:40:50.030 --> 00:40:51.880
But competitive on
knowing where it is

00:40:51.880 --> 00:40:55.810
and ending it-- that's the best
way to be competitive on this.

00:40:55.810 --> 00:40:57.570
Yeah.

00:40:57.570 --> 00:40:59.170
Thank you everyone for coming.

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:00.930
Thanks everyone
who are watching.

